{"key":"processedPost-12476485","value":{"id":12476485,"first":12476075,"last":12484320,"when":1272556810,"utime":"04/29/10 07:00 PM","content":"A couple of points need to be considered here.&nbsp; If you stack them after first flush, you protect the contaminant spores that have landed on the surfaces that are then sandwiched, allowing them to germinate more easily.<br /><br />In addition, the substrates will dry out much sooner, because you have six sides exposed to air instead of one side.&nbsp; If you try to crank up the humidifier to make up for this, you lose a major pinning trigger.&nbsp; A humidifier is only supposed to provide humidity.&nbsp; It's not intended to replace substrate moisture or keep it steady.&nbsp; Using a humidifier in this way will negatively effect pinning.&nbsp; You shouldn't have visible moisture on the surface of a substrate from a humidifier.&nbsp; That's the job of misting, and then the substrate needs to dry somewhat before the next misting session.&nbsp; It's the ebb and flow of moisture content that is one of the big pinning triggers.&nbsp; I wouldn't stack large substrates, especially after a flush.<br /><br />I'd also put the humidifier on the bottom, not the top.&nbsp; Humidity tends to stratify towards the top of a mini-greenhouse anyway, so putting the humidifier on the bottom mixes the air up more.<br />RR","title":"Re: stacking colonized blocks in mini greenhouse?"}}